passages.text: Today's Morning Meeting | Also Published Today | Key Changes | JPM Events | Upcoming Earnings
AFL | European Capital Goods (Phil Buller)

We are mindful of the "wood for the trees" idiom when it comes to the electricals subgroup; the multi- year out- growth of electrical equipment investment versus GDP is almost as certain as death and taxes, but there are important near- term factors to overlay which drive our ratings and Dec 2026 price targets. We see the most upside risk to consensus at Legrand and in Siemens' SI division, based on our analysis of DC, US office, resi, and discrete automation, as explored herein. We are OW Legrand (from NR) with a PT of €165, which we transfer to Phil Buller and add to our AFL. We are Neutral ABB (from NR) (CHF 55) and Neutral Schneider (from NR) (€220), having published on Siemens at OW (€300) yesterday (link).

The Global Beauty segment remained subdued with most players disappointing on top- line during reporting, evidencing that demand challenges are persisting. In this note, we provide an overview of the current market dynamics, with a read- across from global beauty peers, and also assess market expectations for European players post H1. We conclude that the global market growth should remain below historical trends at c3%. Over H225, we see a measured sequential acceleration in demand driven by China and the US, though signals for both are mixed, with risks of US destocking and China competition rising, while W. Europe may decelerate further. It has been a contrasting earnings season for European beauty players, with exaggerated valuation discrepancies and positioning benefitting L'Oreal the most. Looking into H225 expectations - with the market still expecting a sequential H2 acceleration - we see Beiersdorf offering the most compelling risk/reward into H2 at a valuation of 21x PE26E (16x ex- cash) and 9x EV/EBITDA26E. We also flag our fundamentally positive preference on Unilever (OW) as we see evidence of the reshaping of the portfolio towards Beauty & Personal Care as a driver of value creation. L'Oreal's solid H1 has anchored the stock as a must own stock amid a turbulent reporting, yet we flag H2 consensus has risen further paying a tough hurdle amid still subdued Beauty demand.
